00:52:53.210 --> 00:52:54.530
- Thank you, Jim.

00:52:54.530 --> 00:52:57.850
- [Man] Terrestrial mammals, obviously,

00:52:57.850 --> 00:53:01.340
mostly breathing is involuntary,
but aquatic mammals,

00:53:01.340 --> 00:53:04.960
it seems need much more
of a voluntary mechanism

00:53:04.960 --> 00:53:07.430
to control breathing so they don't drown

00:53:07.430 --> 00:53:08.263
when they're submerging.

00:53:08.263 --> 00:53:10.930
Are there any differences in the circuits

00:53:10.930 --> 00:53:13.980
that regulate breathing in them?

00:53:13.980 --> 00:53:18.980
- Well, that's a very interesting
question, Jim, thank you.

00:53:19.280 --> 00:53:24.000
Diving mammals have a
lot of specializations.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:26.310
And we actually still have some of them.

00:53:26.310 --> 00:53:28.410
It's called a diving reflex.

00:53:28.410 --> 00:53:30.950
So if you splash cold water on yourself,

00:53:30.950 --> 00:53:32.690
you may initiate the diving reflex.

00:53:32.690 --> 00:53:37.690
And what the diving reflex
does is, you stop breathing,

00:53:37.730 --> 00:53:42.350
you stop your circulation
from going anywhere

00:53:42.350 --> 00:53:44.340
except the two most critical organs:

00:53:44.340 --> 00:53:46.510
your heart and your brain.

00:53:46.510 --> 00:53:48.400
And if you're a diving whale, it'll go to

00:53:48.400 --> 00:53:51.270
your extremely efficient tail muscle.

00:53:51.270 --> 00:53:54.560
And the rate of oxygen consumption

00:53:54.560 --> 00:53:56.633
then gets reduced tremendously.

00:53:57.470 --> 00:54:01.710
Every year we have young
children fall through the ice.

00:54:01.710 --> 00:54:04.990
And they could be submerged
for a half an hour and more

00:54:04.990 --> 00:54:07.420
and they can survive.

00:54:07.420 --> 00:54:11.000
And the reason they survive
is, one, diving reflex,

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:12.840
and two, because they're small,

00:54:12.840 --> 00:54:16.770
their surface area to
body volume is so small,

00:54:16.770 --> 00:54:19.030
they cool down quickly enough so

00:54:19.030 --> 00:54:22.020
that four-minute oxygen that we have

00:54:22.020 --> 00:54:24.520
can now last them 30 or 40 minutes,

00:54:24.520 --> 00:54:27.190
whereas you and I, if
we went below the water,

00:54:27.190 --> 00:54:29.460
we wouldn't cool off fast enough.

00:54:29.460 --> 00:54:32.120
So I don't know if that
really answered your question,

00:54:32.120 --> 00:54:33.770
but that's as close as I can get.

00:54:35.390 --> 00:54:36.390
- [Woman] Thank you.

00:54:37.350 --> 00:54:39.340
Here, I'll stand up.

00:54:39.340 --> 00:54:41.790
I don't quite know what my question is,

00:54:41.790 --> 00:54:44.273
but it's about apnea, sleep apnea.

00:54:45.950 --> 00:54:47.920
It seems to be being diagnosed

00:54:47.920 --> 00:54:51.200
much, much more frequently these days

00:54:51.200 --> 00:54:53.300
and not just in people with CPAPs,

00:54:53.300 --> 00:54:58.053
but people who, I don't
know, snore a little.

00:54:59.568 --> 00:55:02.800
And I guess I, I'm in the second category,

00:55:02.800 --> 00:55:06.460
and I'm just wondering if you,
and we're always told that

00:55:06.460 --> 00:55:10.540
there're really dire
consequences of apnea.

00:55:10.540 --> 00:55:12.428
Oh, okay, so that's the answer.

00:55:12.428 --> 00:55:13.400
(audience laughing)

00:55:13.400 --> 00:55:15.920
- Well, I could explain a little bit.

00:55:15.920 --> 00:55:20.380
So, you stop breathing,
you're still using oxygen,

00:55:20.380 --> 00:55:22.500
so your oxygen levels drop,

00:55:22.500 --> 00:55:23.853
depending how long you're not breathing,

00:55:23.853 --> 00:55:27.090
your oxygen levels can drop to the point

00:55:27.090 --> 00:55:29.980
where they can begin to do damage.

00:55:29.980 --> 00:55:32.140
Now remember, you're not
just stopping breathing,

00:55:32.140 --> 00:55:34.930
people with sleep apnea, once per night.

00:55:34.930 --> 00:55:37.750
It can be as many as 400 times a night,

00:55:37.750 --> 00:55:39.480
people stop breathing,

00:55:39.480 --> 00:55:42.380
and the only way they
start again is to wake up.

00:55:42.380 --> 00:55:46.020
So that has the consequences
of disrupting sleep,

00:55:46.020 --> 00:55:49.580
exposing all their cells,
but particularly their brain

00:55:49.580 --> 00:55:52.040
to extended periods of low oxygen,

00:55:52.040 --> 00:55:56.290
and their blood pressure
can often shoot up

00:55:56.290 --> 00:55:58.810
to well over 200 systolic.

00:55:58.810 --> 00:56:02.000
So you imagine it happening,
this hundreds of times a night,

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:05.980
and the cumulative effect
over time is just devastating.

00:56:05.980 --> 00:56:08.830
Now, the therapy that works are

00:56:08.830 --> 00:56:10.740
these positive pressure ventilators.

00:56:10.740 --> 00:56:13.660
The problem is, most people hate them

00:56:13.660 --> 00:56:15.310
and there's a lot of effort

00:56:15.310 --> 00:56:17.860
to try and find alternative mechanisms

00:56:17.860 --> 00:56:20.720
that can keep people
ventilating all night.

00:56:20.720 --> 00:56:22.425
Did that answer your question?

00:56:22.425 --> 00:56:23.390
(woman speaking in background)

00:56:23.390 --> 00:56:24.614
Like snoring.

00:56:24.614 --> 00:56:25.960
- [Woman] Yeah.

00:56:25.960 --> 00:56:29.980
- NIH says that people who
snore have three to five times

00:56:29.980 --> 00:56:34.850
the rate of incidence of
strokes and heart attacks.

00:56:34.850 --> 00:56:38.790
Snorers, not people
with frank sleep apnea.

00:56:38.790 --> 00:56:40.690
So snoring in and of itself is

00:56:40.690 --> 00:56:43.363
something that is a matter of concern.

00:56:44.900 --> 00:56:46.450
I don't mean to alarm you, but.

00:56:47.660 --> 00:56:48.530
- [Woman] Hi.

00:56:48.530 --> 00:56:51.550
Since we sometimes
historically have thought of

00:56:51.550 --> 00:56:54.330
basic mechanisms in terms
of the male model of human,

00:56:54.330 --> 00:56:55.670
I just wonder--

00:56:55.670 --> 00:56:56.856
- Excuse me, the?

00:56:56.856 --> 00:57:00.410
- [Woman] Sometimes we
think of basic mechanisms

00:57:00.410 --> 00:57:02.880
in terms of a male model of human being,

00:57:02.880 --> 00:57:04.020
as opposed to both genders.

00:57:04.020 --> 00:57:06.410
And I'm just wondering
if your research includes

00:57:06.410 --> 00:57:09.380
any potential differences in females.

00:57:09.380 --> 00:57:12.230
Because if you're linking the entry points

00:57:12.230 --> 00:57:13.780
and neural networks, you know,

00:57:13.780 --> 00:57:16.530
I just wonder if you've
seen any differences

00:57:16.530 --> 00:57:17.990
between male and female or--

00:57:17.990 --> 00:57:20.610
- We haven't, at the level
we've been looking at,

00:57:20.610 --> 00:57:22.160
we have not seen any differences.

00:57:22.160 --> 00:57:26.260
However, demographically, for sleep apnea

00:57:26.260 --> 00:57:29.540
women seem to be
protected until menopause.

00:57:29.540 --> 00:57:33.140
And then at menopause, their
rate of sleep apnea rises.

00:57:33.140 --> 00:57:36.660
So it's something about the
protective effects, probably,

00:57:36.660 --> 00:57:40.610
of hormones that are
reducing the likelihood

00:57:40.610 --> 00:57:44.500
that women becomes, have
obstructive sleep apnea.

00:57:44.500 --> 00:57:46.910
But as soon as they pass menopause,

00:57:46.910 --> 00:57:49.650
their rate of sleep apnea goes up.

